Added documentation.  Protocol validator was run.

Is this important here that we construct a single string and append twice?

Does this chained concat generate temporary multiple strings?
In this case, I don't believe it does given the operator rules in c++, and clang-tidy doesn't warn on it.

Ask a further question, do you know hwy this doesn't apply

https://clang.llvm.org/extra/clang-tidy/checks/performance/inefficient-string-concatenation.html
Hmm, is this really indented to be in this patch? You +2ed this patch? To me these changes are not relevant.

I'm not following how they're not relevant.  This function needed to be broken out so that we could do a comparison of the user values on line 2001, which is required for implementing this feature.  Can you elaborate on why this isn't relevant to this patch?

Okay, rephrased. "This commit implements that behavior for one handler ManagerAccount.", do we expect every handler implement similar logic?

The previous if-none-match header handles all the resources, right?

> Okay, rephrased. "This commit implements that behavior for one handler ManagerAccount.", do we expect every handler implement similar logic?

Not necessarily.  The spec doesn't REQUIRE it in all cases.

> 
> The previous if-none-match header handles all the resources, right?

Correct, but that was able to be done generically for all requests with a direct comparison.  It's not clear to me in code how to implement if-none-match generically, and because it's only required for ManagerAccount, I did the minimum required to get us to pass protocol validator.

That should've read:
"It's not clear to me in code how to implement if-match generically"

> Not necessarily.  The spec doesn't REQUIRE it in all cases.
>  because it's only required for ManagerAccount

Hmm, where is that? Isn't If-Match an HTTP requirement?

IIUC, Redfish-Protocol-Validator just happens to use certain resource to test this header. Like what they have done in Usercase-Validator: they don't test expand on every URL.

> I did the minimum required to get us to pass protocol validator

I understood this that this commit can pass the test case in Redfish-Protocol-Validator

> > Not necessarily.  The spec doesn't REQUIRE it in all cases.
> >  because it's only required for ManagerAccount
> 
> Hmm, where is that? Isn't If-Match an HTTP requirement?

The HTTP RFC does not specify it as a requirement on all endpoints.  There are LOTS of web servers that don't implement it.

> 
> IIUC, Redfish-Protocol-Validator just happens to use certain resource to test this header. Like what they have done in Usercase-Validator: they don't test expand on every URL.


That's a really good point, we would have to add similar code elsewhere if we wanted to do this in more cases.  Can you think of a cleaner way to implement this?  That's why I originally put it up for review months ago.  I'm happy to refactor if there's a cleaner way, but I'm not seeing one at this moment.

> 
> > I did the minimum required to get us to pass protocol validator
> 
> I understood this that this commit can pass the test case in Redfish-Protocol-Validator

> Can you think of a cleaner way to implement this? 

I haven't thought into details, just throw my comments. Why do other maintainers think?

It's weird to me that users see different header behaviors across resources.
kryzysztof already +1ed it.  I guess Gunnar hasn't looked at it yet.

> It's weird to me that users see different header behaviors across resources.

Nan, any more input here on what you think we should do?

I will let you decide. This inconsistency is bad. Just throw my rough ideas of a cleaner way: user can register a callback, like |updateUserValues| here, then most codes in |handleIfMatch| can be shared.

I don't like blocking people because of some imperfection as I believe things can evolve with more iterations, as long as it doesn't introduce fatal mistakes. So I +1 this change.
So handleIfMatch should be put in a common layer?  That makes some sense to me, I can try to make that change.
Take a look at what's up there now.  It has other compromises in that we have to make some copies of the Request object, but I think is more in line with what you were thinking?

I thought we hit problems in the past copying the Request object since it includes the body payload?

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/commit/a3e65892add97ce68816c1544c0aa21591239fc7

https://discord.com/channels/775381525260664832/855566794994221117/888171699625934908

> I thought we hit problems in the past copying the Request object since it includes the body payload?

That was because the Request payload for firmware update was quite large for non-tree updates (ie firmware) and was running the bmc out of ram.  I agree, the Request object copy isn't great.....  but I don't see a good way to effect a non-copy non-move without first cleaning up the mess in http/router authorization (which I've been trying to do unsuccessfully for a while now), or making a copy.  In this case, we only make a copy if we're doing If-Match, and we should only do if-match on Redfish-tree operations, never on firmware update payloads, so I think we're safe as far as the external interface is concerned.  I can look at trying to clean up and get a copy-less version of this going, but this patch is already pretty large, and the external interface is correct, even if the code is sub-optimal.

Seem reasonable?
Yeah I am good. Getting Redfish protocol validator passes is great, we can incrementally improve this. Great work. Thanks!
Will an empty JSON map to a unique hash value?

no, it wont in this design.  Given that we can have non-json payloads, that was a compromise that I made in this design (same as before)

Was there a change that you thought should be made here?

This works here since we return early when |ifMatch| in the request header is empty, right?

Ack.
Can't do const reference.  This is what I was talking about before, where we require a copy of request.

I don't get it, won't std::bind_front copy a req itself?

Here we copy this |request| multiple times

If you change this to a const reference, this code no longer compiles.  I can't fully understand the move/copy semantics in this case, but if you know what needs to be done, I'm happy to make the change.

It didn't compile because |app| doesn't take const reference to the request.

I am not just randomly sending comments. I did experiments on this yesterday before I made such comment. If we don't use reference, we will call the copy constructor of Request multiple times.

So, this compiles,

```
void afterIfMatchRequest(crow::App& app,
                         const std::shared_ptr<bmcweb::AsyncResp>& asyncResp,
                         crow::Request& req,
                         std::string_view ifMatchHeader,
                         const crow::Response& resIn)
```

I believe std::bind_front does a copy first. Then it pass that copy as a reference to this |afterIfMatchRequest| function.

I never said you were randomly sending comments.  If it was implied by my response, I apologize, but it's definitely not what I intended.  My point was that I had tried what you suggested, and it didn't work.

> So, this compiles,

Ok, so different than your original comment, using a non-const reference looks like it works?  I thought I had tried that, but apparently I was mistaken, let me give it a shot.

Thanks for looking at it.

Cool, thanks 👍 I tested compilation but not testing possible lifetime issues here. I tested lifetime issues in my dummy workspace codes and no lifetime issues were found: std::bind_if does copy a |req|
In the lastest patchset this is now a reference.
If you the handler here, does it only run when there is a query parameter?
I don't think so?  It only runs if the query params were valid, which I think is ok?

I got it wrong. The optional return value of |parseParameters| is just to indicate parsing errors.

No question here.
Accidental rebase.  Still roughly the same content.

Has been in review for a while now, has gotten reviews from all maintainers that I'd expect to look at it, and should be zero low-impact for existing queries (feature is only enabled for queries sporting if-match).

As always, happy to discuss/revert if there's other issues, but everyone I'd expect to weigh in on this series has, so lets get the protocol validator passing!
No, this is an intentional copy, because the bind_front on line 97 needs to capture by value.  I thought about doing the copy on line 97 inline, but that seemed worse.
I guess the answer is actually "yes", this copy is intentional.
